[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] In computer science, a **generalized suffix tree** is a suffix tree for a set of strings.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] Given the set of strings $D=S_{1},S_{2},\dots ,S_{d}$ of total length n , it is a Patricia tree containing all n suffixes of the strings.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] It can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time and space, and can be used to find all z occurrences of a string P of length m in $O(m+z)$ time, which is asymptotically optimal (assuming the size of the alphabet is constant).
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] When constructing such a tree, each string should be padded with a unique out-of-alphabet marker symbol (or string) to ensure no suffix is a substring of another, guaranteeing each suffix is represented by a unique leaf node.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] Algorithms for constructing a GST include Ukkonen's algorithm (1995) and McCreight's algorithm (1976).
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] A suffix tree for the strings `ABAB` and `BABA` is shown in a figure above.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] They are padded with the unique terminator strings `$0` and `$1`.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] The numbers in the leaf nodes are string number and starting position.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] Notice how a left to right traversal of the leaf nodes corresponds to the sorted order of the suffixes.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] The terminators might be strings or unique single symbols.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] Edges on `$` from the root are left out in this example.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] An alternative to building a generalized suffix tree is to concatenate the strings, and build a regular suffix tree or suffix array for the resulting string.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/generalized-suffix-tree] When hits are evaluated after a search, global positions are mapped into documents and local positions with some algorithm and/or data structure, such as a binary search in the starting/ending positions of the documents.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] In computer science, a **longest common substring** of two or more strings is a longest string that is a substring of all of them.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] There may be more than one longest common substring.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] Applications include data deduplication and plagiarism detection.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] Unlike the longest common subsequence problem, which finds insertions or deletions within the common text, the longest common substring problem seeks a contiguous substring shared by both texts.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] The picture shows two strings where the problem has multiple solutions.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] Although the substring occurrences always overlap, it is impossible to obtain a longer common substring by "uniting" them.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] The strings "ABABC", "BABCA" and "ABCBA" have only one longest common substring, viz.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] Other common substrings are "A", "AB", "B", "BA", "BC" and "C".
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] Given two strings, S of length m and T of length n , find a longest string which is substring of both S and T .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] A generalization is the *k*-**common substring problem**.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] Find for each $2\leq k\leq K$ , a longest string which occurs as substring of at least k strings.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] One can find the lengths and starting positions of the longest common substrings of S and T in $\Theta$ $(n+m)$ time with the help of a generalized suffix tree.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] A faster algorithm can be achieved in the word RAM model of computation if the size $\sigma$ of the input alphabet is in $2^{o\left({\sqrt {\log(n+m)}}\right)}$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] In particular, this algorithm runs in ${\textstyle O\left((n+m)\log \sigma /{\sqrt {\log(n+m)}}\right)}$ time using $O\left((n+m)\log \sigma /\log(n+m)\right)$ space.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] Solving the problem by dynamic programming costs $\Theta (nm)$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] The solutions to the generalized problem take $\Theta (n_{1}+\cdots +n_{K})$ space and $\Theta (n_{1}\cdots n_{K})$ time with dynamic programming and take $\Theta (n_{1}+\cdots +n_{K})$ time with a generalized suffix tree.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] The longest common substrings of a set of strings can be found by building a generalized suffix tree for the strings, and then finding the deepest internal nodes which have leaf nodes from all the strings in the subtree below it.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] The figure on the right is the suffix tree for the strings "ABAB", "BABA" and "ABBA", padded with unique string terminators, to become "ABAB$0", "BABA$1" and "ABBA$2".
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] The nodes representing "A", "B", "AB" and "BA" all have descendant leaves from all of the strings, numbered 0, 1 and 2.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] Building the suffix tree takes $\Theta (N)$ time (if the size of the alphabet is constant).
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] If the tree is traversed from the bottom up with a bit vector telling which strings are seen below each node, the k-common substring problem can be solved in $\Theta (NK)$ time.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] If the suffix tree is prepared for constant time lowest common ancestor retrieval, it can be solved in $\Theta (N)$ time.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] The array `L` stores the length of the longest common suffix of the prefixes `S[1..i]` and `T[1..j]` which *end at position* `i` and `j`, respectively.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] The variable `z` is used to hold the length of the longest common substring found so far.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] The set `ret` is used to hold the set of strings which are of length `z`.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] The set `ret` can be saved efficiently by just storing the index `i`, which is the last character of the longest common substring (of size z) instead of `S[(i-z+1)..i]`.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/longest-common-substring] Thus all the longest common substrings would be, for each i in `ret`, `S[(ret[i]-z)..(ret[i])]`.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/substring-index] In computer science, a **substring index** is a data structure which gives substring search in a text or text collection in sublinear time.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/substring-index] Once constructed from a document or set of documents, a substring index can be used to locate all occurrences of a pattern in time linear or near-linear in the pattern size, with no dependence or only logarithmic dependence on the document size.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/substring-index] The phrase **full-text index** is often used for substring indexes.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/substring-index] But this is ambiguous, as it is also used for regular word indexes such as inverted files and document retrieval.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/substring-index] These data structures typically treat their text and pattern as strings over a fixed alphabet, and search for locations where the pattern occurs as a substring of the text.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In computer science, a **suffix automaton** is an efficient data structure for representing the substring index of a given string which allows the storage, processing, and retrieval of compressed information about all its substrings.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The suffix automaton of a string S is the smallest directed acyclic graph with a dedicated initial vertex and a set of "final" vertices, such that paths from the initial vertex to final vertices represent the suffixes of the string.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In terms of automata theory, a suffix automaton is the minimal partial deterministic finite automaton that recognizes the set of suffixes of a given string $S=s_{1}s_{2}\dots s_{n}$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The state graph of a suffix automaton is called a directed acyclic word graph (DAWG), a term that is also sometimes used for any deterministic acyclic finite state automaton.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Suffix automata were introduced in 1983 by a group of scientists from the University of Denver and the University of Colorado Boulder.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] They suggested a linear time online algorithm for its construction and showed that the suffix automaton of a string S having length at least two characters has at most ${\textstyle 2|S|-1}$ states and at most ${\textstyle 3|S|-4}$ transitions.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Further works have shown a close connection between suffix automata and suffix trees, and have outlined several generalizations of suffix automata, such as compacted suffix automaton obtained by compression of nodes with a single outgoing arc.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Suffix automata provide efficient solutions to problems such as substring search and computation of the largest common substring of two and more strings.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In their initial work, Blumer *et al*. showed a suffix automaton built for the string S of length greater than 1 has at most $2|S|-1$ states and at most $3|S|-4$ transitions, and suggested a linear algorithm for automaton construction.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In 1983, Mu-Tian Chen and Joel Seiferas independently showed that Weiner's 1973 suffix-tree construction algorithm while building a suffix tree of the string S constructs a suffix automaton of the reversed string ${\textstyle S^{R}}$ as an auxiliary structure.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In 1987, Blumer *et al*. applied the compressing technique used in suffix trees to a suffix automaton and invented the compacted suffix automaton, which is also called the compacted directed acyclic word graph (CDAWG).
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In 1997, Maxime Crochemore and Renaud Vérin developed a linear algorithm for direct CDAWG construction.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In 2001, Shunsuke Inenaga *et al*. developed an algorithm for construction of CDAWG for a set of words given by a trie.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In terms of its diagram, the automaton recognizes the word $\omega =\omega _{1}\omega _{2}\dots \omega _{m}$ only if there is a path from the initial vertex $q_{0}$ to some final vertex $q\in F$ such that concatenation of characters on this path forms $\omega$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The set of words recognized by an automaton forms a language that is set to be recognized by the automaton.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In these terms, the language recognized by a suffix automaton of S is the language of its (possibly empty) suffixes.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] "Right context" of the word $\omega$ with respect to language L is a set $[\omega ]_{R}=\{\alpha :\omega \alpha \in L\}$ that is a set of words $\alpha$ such that their concatenation with $\omega$ forms a word from L .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Right contexts induce a natural equivalence relation $[\alpha ]_{R}=[\beta ]_{R}$ on the set of all words.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] If language L is recognized by some deterministic finite automaton, there exists unique up to isomorphism automaton that recognizes the same language and has the minimum possible number of states.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Such an automaton is called a minimal automaton for the given language L .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In these terms, a "suffix automaton" is the minimal deterministic finite automaton recognizing the language of suffixes of the word $S=s_{1}s_{2}\dots s_{n}$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The right context of the word $\omega$ with respect to this language consists of words $\alpha$ , such that $\omega \alpha$ is a suffix of S .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] For example, for the word $S=abacaba$ and its subword $\omega =ab$ , it holds $endpos(ab)=\{2,6\}$ and $[ab]_{R}=\{a,acaba\}$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Informally, $[ab]_{R}$ is formed by words that follow occurrences of $ab$ to the end of S and $endpos(ab)$ is formed by right positions of those occurrences.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In this example, the element $x=2\in endpos(ab)$ corresponds with the word $s_{3}s_{4}s_{5}s_{6}s_{7}=acaba\in [ab]_{R}$ while the word $a\in [ab]_{R}$ corresponds with the element $7-|a|=6\in endpos(ab)$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] It implies several structure properties of suffix automaton states.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Any state $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ of the suffix automaton recognizes some continuous chain of nested suffixes of the longest word recognized by this state.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] "Left extension" ${\overset {\scriptstyle {\leftarrow }}{\gamma }}$ of the string $\gamma$ is the longest string $\omega$ that has the same right context as $\gamma$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Length $|{\overset {\scriptstyle {\leftarrow }}{\gamma }}|$ of the longest string recognized by $q=[\gamma ]_{R}$ is denoted by $len(q)$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] "Suffix link" $link(q)$ of the state $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ is the pointer to the state p that contains the largest suffix of $\alpha$ that is not recognized by q .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In this terms it can be said $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ recognizes exactly all suffixes of ${\overset {\scriptstyle {\leftarrow }}{\alpha }}$ that is longer than $len(link(q))$ and not longer than $len(q)$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Edges E of the tree connect pairs of vertices $({\overleftarrow {\omega }},{\overleftarrow {\alpha \omega }})$ , such that $\alpha \in \Sigma$ and ${\overleftarrow {\omega }}\neq {\overleftarrow {\alpha \omega }}$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] A "prefix tree" (or "trie") is a rooted directed tree in which arcs are marked by characters in such a way no vertex v of such tree has two out-going arcs marked with the same character.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Some vertices in trie are marked as final.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Trie is said to recognize a set of words defined by paths from its root to final vertices.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In this way prefix trees are a special kind of deterministic finite automata if you perceive its root as an initial vertex.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The "suffix trie" of the word S is a prefix tree recognizing a set of its suffixes.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] "A suffix tree" is a tree obtained from a suffix trie via the compaction procedure, during which consequent edges are merged if the degree of the vertex between them is equal to two.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] By its definition, a suffix automaton can be obtained via minimization of the suffix trie.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] It may be shown that a compacted suffix automaton is obtained by both minimization of the suffix tree (if one assumes each string on the edge of the suffix tree is a solid character from the alphabet) and compaction of the suffix automaton.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Besides this connection between the suffix tree and the suffix automaton of the same string there is as well a connection between the suffix automaton of the string $S=s_{1}s_{2}\dots s_{n}$ and the suffix tree of the reversed string $S^{R}=s_{n}s_{n-1}\dots s_{1}$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] A suffix automaton of the string S of length $n>1$ has at most $2n-1$ states and at most $3n-4$ transitions.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] These bounds are reached on strings $abb\dots bb=ab^{n-1}$ and $abb\dots bc=ab^{n-2}c$ correspondingly.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] This may be formulated in a stricter way as $|\delta |\leq |Q|+n-2$ where $|\delta |$ and $|Q|$ are the numbers of transitions and states in automaton correspondingly.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Initially the automaton only consists of a single state corresponding to the empty word, then characters of the string are added one by one and the automaton is rebuilt on each step incrementally.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] After a new character is appended to the string, some equivalence classes are altered.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Let $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}$ be the right context of $\alpha$ with respect to the language of $\omega$ suffixes.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] After adding x to the current word $\omega$ the right context of $\alpha$ may change significantly only if $\alpha$ is a suffix of $\omega x$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] It implies equivalence relation $\equiv _{R_{\omega x}}$ is a refinement of $\equiv _{R_{\omega }}$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] After the addition of a new character at most two equivalence classes of $\equiv _{R_{\omega }}$ will be split and each of them may split in at most two new classes.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] First, equivalence class corresponding to empty right context is always split into two equivalence classes, one of them corresponding to $\omega x$ itself and having $\{\varepsilon \}$ as a right context.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] This new equivalence class contains exactly $\omega x$ and all its suffixes that did not occur in $\omega$ , as the right context of such words was empty before and contains only empty word now.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Given the correspondence between states of the suffix automaton and vertices of the suffix tree, it is possible to find out the second state that may possibly split after a new character is appended.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The transition from $\omega$ to $\omega x$ corresponds to the transition from $\omega ^{R}$ to $x\omega ^{R}$ in the reversed string.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In terms of suffix trees it corresponds to the insertion of the new longest suffix $x\omega ^{R}$ into the suffix tree of $\omega ^{R}$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] At most two new vertices may be formed after this insertion: one of them corresponding to $x\omega ^{R}$ , while the other one corresponds to its direct ancestor if there was a branching.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Returning to suffix automata, it means the first new state recognizes $\omega x$ and the second one (if there is a second new state) is its suffix link.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] It implies that if $\alpha =\beta$ (for example, when x didn't occur in $\omega$ at all and $\alpha =\beta =\varepsilon$ ), then only the equivalence class corresponding to the empty right context is split.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Besides suffix links it is also needed to define final states of the automaton.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] It follows from structure properties that all suffixes of a word $\alpha$ recognized by $q=[\alpha ]_{R}$ are recognized by some vertex on *suffix path* $(q,link(q),link^{2}(q),\dots )$ of q .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Namely, suffixes with length greater than $len(link(q))$ lie in q , suffixes with length greater than $len(link(link(q))$ but not greater than $len(link(q))$ lie in $link(q)$ and so on.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Thus if the state recognizing $\omega$ is denoted by $last$ , then all final states (that is, recognizing suffixes of $\omega$ ) form up the sequence $(last,link(last),link^{2}(last),\dots )$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] After the character x is appended to $\omega$ possible new states of suffix automaton are $[\omega x]_{R_{\omega x}}$ and $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega x}}$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Words from $[\omega x]_{R_{\omega x}}$ occur in $\omega x$ only as its suffixes therefore there should be no transitions at all from $[\omega x]_{R_{\omega x}}$ while transitions to it should go from suffixes of $\omega$ having length at least $\alpha$ and be marked with the character x .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] State $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega x}}$ is formed by subset of $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}$ , thus transitions from $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega x}}$ should be same as from $[\alpha ]_{R_{\omega }}$ .
