[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Complexity of the algorithm may vary depending on the underlying structure used to store transitions of the automaton.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] It may be implemented in $O(n\log |\Sigma |)$ with $O(n)$ memory overhead or in $O(n)$ with $O(n|\Sigma |)$ memory overhead if one assumes that memory allocation is done in $O(1)$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] To obtain such complexity, one has to use the methods of amortized analysis.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The value of $len(p)$ strictly reduces with each iteration of the cycle while it may only increase by as much as one after the first iteration of the cycle on the next *add_letter* call.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Overall value of $len(p)$ never exceeds n and it is only increased by one between iterations of appending new letters that suggest total complexity is at most linear as well.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The linearity of the second cycle is shown in a similar way.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The suffix automaton is closely related to other suffix structures and substring indices.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Given a suffix automaton of a specific string one may construct its suffix tree via compacting and recursive traversal in linear time.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Similar transforms are possible in both directions to switch between the suffix automaton of S and the suffix tree of reversed string $S^{R}$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] As was already mentioned above, a compacted suffix automaton is obtained via both compaction of a regular suffix automaton (by removing states which are non-final and have exactly one out-going arc) and the minimization of a suffix tree.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Similarly to the regular suffix automaton, states of compacted suffix automaton may be defined in explicit manner.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] *A two-way extension* ${\overset {\scriptstyle {\longleftrightarrow }}{\gamma }}$ of a word $\gamma$ is the longest word $\omega =\beta \gamma \alpha$ , such that every occurrence of $\gamma$ in S is preceded by $\beta$ and succeeded by $\alpha$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Two-way extensions induce an equivalence relation ${\textstyle {\overset {\scriptstyle \longleftrightarrow }{\alpha }}={\overset {\scriptstyle \longleftrightarrow }{\beta }}}$ which defines the set of words recognized by the same state of compacted automaton.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] If words $\alpha$ and $\beta$ have same right extensions, and words $\beta$ and $\gamma$ have same left extensions, then cumulatively all strings $\alpha$ , $\beta$ and $\gamma$ have same two-way extensions.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] At the same time it may happen that neither left nor right extensions of $\alpha$ and $\gamma$ coincide.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The total number of equivalence classes for this relation does not exceed $n+1$ which implies that compacted suffix automaton of the string having length n has at most $n+1$ states.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The amount of transitions in such automaton is at most $2n-2$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] It is possible to construct a generalization of suffix automaton that would recognize the language formed up by suffixes of all words from the set.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Constraints for the number of states and transitions in such automaton would stay the same as for a single-word automaton if you put $n=|S_{1}|+|S_{2}|+\dots +|S_{k}|$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] This idea is further generalized to the case when T is not given explicitly but instead is given by a prefix tree with Q vertices.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Mohri *et al*. showed such an automaton would have at most $2Q-2$ and may be constructed in linear time from its size.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Some compression algorithms, such as LZ77 and RLE may benefit from storing suffix automaton or similar structure not for the whole string but for only last k its characters while the string is updated.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] This is because compressing data is usually expressively large and using $O(n)$ memory is undesirable.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] In 1985, Janet Blumer developed an algorithm to maintain a suffix automaton on a sliding window of size k in $O(nk)$ worst-case and $O(n\log k)$ on average, assuming characters are distributed independently and uniformly.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] A variation of McCreight's suffix tree construction algorithm for this task was suggested in 1989 by Edward Fiala and Daniel Greene; several years later a similar result was obtained with the variation of Ukkonen's algorithm by Jesper Larsson.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] One way to overcome this obstacle is to allow window width to vary a bit while staying $O(k)$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] It may be achieved by an approximate algorithm suggested by Inenaga et al. in 2004.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] The window for which suffix automaton is built in this algorithm is not guaranteed to be of length k but it is guaranteed to be at least k and at most $2k+1$ while providing linear overall complexity of the algorithm.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] It is assumed here that T is given on the input after suffix automaton of S is constructed.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-automaton] Suffix automata are also used in data compression, music retrieval and matching on genome sequences.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] In computer science, a **suffix tree** (also called **PAT tree** or, in an earlier form, **position tree**) is a compressed trie containing all the suffixes of the given text as their keys and positions in the text as their values.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Suffix trees allow particularly fast implementations of many important string operations.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The construction of such a tree for the string S takes time and space linear in the length of S .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Once constructed, several operations can be performed quickly, such as locating a substring in S , locating a substring if a certain number of mistakes are allowed, and locating matches for a regular expression pattern.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Suffix trees also provided one of the first linear-time solutions for the longest common substring problem.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] These speedups come at a cost: storing a string's suffix tree typically requires significantly more space than storing the string itself.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The concept was first introduced by Weiner (1973).
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Rather than the suffix $S[i..n]$ , Weiner stored in his trie the *prefix identifier* for each position, that is, the shortest string starting at i and occurring only once in S .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] His *Algorithm D* takes an uncompressed trie for $S[k+1..n]$ and extends it into a trie for $S[k..n]$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] This way, starting from the trivial trie for $S[n..n]$ , a trie for $S[1..n]$ can be built by $n-1$ successive calls to Algorithm D; however, the overall run time is $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Weiner's *Algorithm B* maintains several auxiliary data structures, to achieve an overall run time linear in the size of the constructed trie.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The latter can still be $O(n^{2})$ nodes, e.g. for $S=a^{n}b^{n}a^{n}b^{n}\$.$ Weiner's *Algorithm C* finally uses compressed tries to achieve linear overall storage size and run time.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Donald Knuth subsequently characterized the latter as "Algorithm of the Year 1973" according to his student Vaughan Pratt.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The text book Aho, Hopcroft & Ullman (1974, Sect.9.5) reproduced Weiner's results in a simplified and more elegant form, introducing the term *position tree*.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] McCreight (1976) was the first to build a (compressed) trie of all suffixes of S .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Although the suffix starting at i is usually longer than the prefix identifier, their path representations in a compressed trie do not differ in size.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] On the other hand, McCreight could dispense with most of Weiner's auxiliary data structures; only suffix links remained.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Ukkonen (1995) further simplified the construction.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] He provided the first online-construction of suffix trees, now known as Ukkonen's algorithm, with running time that matched the then fastest algorithms.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] These algorithms are all linear-time for a constant-size alphabet, and have worst-case running time of $O(n\log n)$ in general.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Farach (1997) gave the first suffix tree construction algorithm that is optimal for all alphabets.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] In particular, this is the first linear-time algorithm for strings drawn from an alphabet of integers in a polynomial range.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Farach's algorithm has become the basis for new algorithms for constructing both suffix trees and suffix arrays, for example, in external memory, compressed, succinct, etc.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Except for the root, every internal node has at least two children.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Each edge is labelled with a non-empty substring of S .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] No two edges starting out of a node can have string-labels beginning with the same character.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The string obtained by concatenating all the string-labels found on the path from the root to leaf i spells out suffix $S[i..n]$ , for i from 1 to n .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] If a suffix of S is also the prefix of another suffix, such a tree does not exist for the string.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] For example, in the string *abcbc*, the suffix *bc* is also a prefix of the suffix *bcbc*.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] In such a case, the path spelling out *bc* will not end in a leaf, violating the fifth rule.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] To fix this problem, S is padded with a terminal symbol not seen in the string (usually denoted `$`).
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] This ensures that no suffix is a prefix of another, and that there will be n leaf nodes, one for each of the n suffixes of S .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Since all internal non-root nodes are branching, there can be at most $n-1$ such nodes, and $n+(n-1)+1=2n$ nodes in total ( n leaves, $n-1$ internal non-root nodes, 1 root).
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] A generalized suffix tree is a suffix tree made for a set of strings instead of a single string.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] It represents all suffixes from this set of strings.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Each string must be terminated by a different termination symbol.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] A suffix tree for a string S of length n can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, if the letters come from an alphabet of integers in a polynomial range (in particular, this is true for constant-sized alphabets).
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] For larger alphabets, the running time is dominated by first sorting the letters to bring them into a range of size $O(n)$ ; in general, this takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The costs below are given under the assumption that the alphabet is constant.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Assume that a suffix tree has been built for the string S of length n , or that a generalised suffix tree has been built for the set of strings $D=\{S_{1},S_{2},\dots ,S_{K}\}$ of total length $n=n_{1}+n_{2}+\cdots +n_{K}$ .
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The suffix tree can be prepared for constant time lowest common ancestor retrieval between nodes in $\Theta (n)$ time.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Suffix trees can be used to solve a large number of string problems that occur in text-editing, free-text search, computational biology and other application areas.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Suffix trees are often used in bioinformatics applications, searching for patterns in DNA or protein sequences (which can be viewed as long strings of characters).
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The ability to search efficiently with mismatches might be considered their greatest strength.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Suffix trees are also used in data compression; they can be used to find repeated data, and can be used for the sorting stage of the Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Variants of the LZW compression schemes use suffix trees (LZSS).
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] A suffix tree is also used in suffix tree clustering, a data clustering algorithm used in some search engines.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] If each node and edge can be represented in $\Theta (1)$ space, the entire tree can be represented in $\Theta (n)$ space.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The total length of all the strings on all of the edges in the tree is $O(n^{2})$ , but each edge can be stored as the position and length of a substring of S, giving a total space usage of $\Theta (n)$ computer words.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The worst-case space usage of a suffix tree is seen with a fibonacci word, giving the full $2n$ nodes.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] An important choice when making a suffix tree implementation is the parent-child relationships between nodes.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The most common is using linked lists called **sibling lists**.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Each node has a pointer to its first child, and to the next node in the child list it is a part of.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Other implementations with efficient running time properties use hash maps, sorted or unsorted arrays (with array doubling), or balanced search trees.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The insertion cost is amortised, and that the costs for hashing are given for perfect hashing.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The large amount of information in each edge and node makes the suffix tree very expensive, consuming about 10 to 20 times the memory size of the source text in good implementations.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Researchers have continued to find smaller indexing structures.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Various parallel algorithms to speed up suffix tree construction have been proposed.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Recently, a practical parallel algorithm for suffix tree construction with $O(n)$ work (sequential time) and $O(\log ^{2}n)$ span has been developed.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The algorithm achieves good parallel scalability on shared-memory multicore machines and can index the human genome – approximately 3GB – in under 3 minutes using a 40-core machine.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] Though linear, the memory usage of a suffix tree is significantly higher than the actual size of the sequence collection.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] For a large text, construction may require external memory approaches.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] There are theoretical results for constructing suffix trees in external memory.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The algorithm by Farach-Colton, Ferragina & Muthukrishnan (2000) is theoretically optimal, with an I/O complexity equal to that of sorting.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] However the overall intricacy of this algorithm has prevented, so far, its practical implementation.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] On the other hand, there have been practical works for constructing disk-based suffix trees which scale to (few) GB/hours.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The state of the art methods are TDD, TRELLIS, DiGeST, and B2ST.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] TDD and TRELLIS scale up to the entire human genome resulting in a disk-based suffix tree of a size in the tens of gigabytes.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] However, these methods cannot handle efficiently collections of sequences exceeding 3 GB.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] DiGeST performs significantly better and is able to handle collections of sequences in the order of 6 GB in about 6 hours.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] All these methods can efficiently build suffix trees for the case when the tree does not fit in main memory, but the input does.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] The most recent method, B2ST, scales to handle inputs that do not fit in main memory.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] ERA is a recent parallel suffix tree construction method that is significantly faster.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] ERA can index the entire human genome in 19 minutes on an 8-core desktop computer with 16 GB RAM.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/suffix-tree] On a simple Linux cluster with 16 nodes (4 GB RAM per node), ERA can index the entire human genome in less than 9 minutes.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] In computer science, **Ukkonen's algorithm** is a linear-time, online algorithm for constructing suffix trees, proposed by Esko Ukkonen in 1995.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] The algorithm begins with an implicit suffix tree containing the first character of the string.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Then it steps through the string, adding successive characters until the tree is complete.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] This order addition of characters gives Ukkonen's algorithm its "on-line" property.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] The original algorithm presented by Peter Weiner in 1973 proceeded backward from the last character to the first one from the shortest to the longest suffix.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] A simpler algorithm was found by Edward M.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] McCreight in 1976, going from the longest to the shortest suffix.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] While generating suffix tree using Ukkonen's algorithm, we will see implicit suffix tree in intermediate steps depending on characters in string S.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] In implicit suffix trees, there will be no edge with $ (or any other termination character) label and no internal node with only one edge going out of it.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Ukkonen's algorithm constructs an implicit suffix tree Ti for each prefix S[1...i] of S (S being the string of length n).
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] It first builds T1 using the 1st character, then T2 using the 2nd character, then T3 using the 3rd character, ..., Tn using the nth character.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Suffix extension is all about adding the next character into the suffix tree built so far.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] In extension j of phase i+1, algorithm finds the end of S[j...i] (which is already in the tree due to previous phase i) and then it extends S[j...i] to be sure the suffix S[j...i+1] is in the tree.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] 2. if the path from the root labelled S[j...i] ends at a non-leaf edge (i.e., there are more characters after S[i] on path) and next character is not S[i+1], then a new leaf edge with label S[i+1] and number j is created starting from character S[i+1].
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] A new internal node will also be created if S[1...i] ends inside (in between) a non-leaf edge.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] If the path from the root labelled S[j..i] ends at a non-leaf edge (i.e., there are more characters after S[i] on path) and next character is S[i+1] (already in tree), do nothing.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] One important point to note is that from a given node (root or internal), there will be one and only one edge starting from one character.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] There will not be more than one edge going out of any node starting with the same character.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] The naive implementation for generating a suffix tree going forward requires *O*(*n*2) or even *O*(*n*3) time complexity in big *O* notation, where *n* is the length of the string.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] By exploiting a number of algorithmic techniques, Ukkonen reduced this to *O*(*n*) (linear) time, for constant-size alphabets, and *O*(*n* log *n*) in general, matching the runtime performance of the earlier two algorithms.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] To better illustrate how a suffix tree is constructed using Ukkonen's algorithm, we can consider the string `S = xabxac`.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Construct $T_{1}$ for `S[1]` by adding the first character of the string.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Rule 2 applies, which creates a new leaf node.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Rule 1 applies, which extends the path label in existing leaf edge.
[src:suffix-tree-algorithm/ukkonen-s-algorithm] Rule 2 applies, which creates a new leaf node (in this case, three new leaf edges and two new internal nodes are created).
